*Dry mouth", Decrease saliva production*; A major feature of *Sjogren syndrome*; accompanied by *dry eyes*
Inflammatory *enlargement of the salivary glands* Complications include:
Increased rates of *dental caries* Candidiasis, Difficulty swallowing and speaking is ___ <br><br>{{c1::Xerostomia}}

A band-like ring of
normal pancreatic tissue that completely encircles the
second portion of the duodenum and produce duodenal obstruction. <br><br>{{c1::Annular pancreas}}

Which carcinomas form
zymogen granules and produce exocrine enzymes such as
trypsin and lipase and develop the syndrome of metastatic fat necrosis caused by the release of lipase into the circulation. <br><br>{{c1::Acinar cell carcinomas}}

Rare neoplasms of the pancreas that occur primarily in children aged 1 to 15 years. They have a distinct
microscopic appearance consisting of squamous islands admixed with acinar cells. They are malignant neoplasms, but survival is better with these tumors than it is for pancreatic
ductal adenocarcinomas. <br><br>{{c1::Pancreatoblastoma}}

A major cause of nephrotic
syndrome in children, with a peak incidence between ages 2 and 6 years. The disease occasionally *follows a respiratory infection* or
*routine immunization*, but it is also associated with *atopic disorders and Hodgkin lymphoma*, characterized by normal glomeruli (minimal change) <br><br>{{c1::Minimal-change disease (MCD)}}

The kidneys are *symmetrically contracted* with diffusely
granular surfaces and a *THINNED CORTEX*. Glomeruli are completely effaced by *hyalinized
connective tissue* with pericarditis, uremic gastroenteritis, and secondary hyperparathyroidism with nephrocalcinosis and renal osteodystrophy. <br><br>{{c1::Chronic Glomerulonephritis}}

Associated with *accelerated hypertension* with *fibrinoid necrosis of arterioles*,
hyperplastic arteriopathy (onion-skinning), necrotizing glomerulitis, and a glomerular thrombotic microangiopathy. proteinuria, hematuria,
papilledema, encephalopathy, cardiovascular abnormalities & *Kidney failure* <br><br>{{c1::Malignant <br>Nephrosclerosis}}

A *hamartomatous lesion composed of vessels,
smooth muscle, and fat*, present in 25% to 50% of
patients with tuberous sclerosis. Clinically significant primarily for their susceptibility to spontaneously *hemorrhage* <br><br>{{c1::Angiomyolipoma}}

Renal cell cancers that occurs in both familial and sporadic forms. The familial form
is associated with mutations of the *MET proto-oncogene* that serves as a tyrosine kinase receptor for hepatocyte growth factor. Morphology -> cuboidal cells arranged in papillary formations, often
with *interstitial foam cells and psammoma bodies* <br><br>{{c1::Papillary carcinoma}}

Due to developmental failure
of the anterior abdominal wall; the bladder communicates directly with the overlying skin or lies as an exposed sac. Complications include chronic infection and an increased incidence
of adenocarcinoma. <br><br>{{c1::Exstrophy of the bladder}}

Occurs in chronic bacterial cystitis (mostly due to E. coli) and more common in
immunosuppressed patients, characterized by yellow, mucosal plaques, composed primarily of foamy
macrophages stuffed with bacterial debris with *Michaelis-Gutmann bodies*. <br><br>{{c1::Malakoplakia}}

Tumor that represents a high-grade lesion of cytologically
*malignant cells present within a flat urothelium*; the
cells often lack cohesiveness and shed into the urine? <br><br>{{c1::Carcinoma in situ (CIS)}}

A benign sexually-transmitted
epithelial proliferation caused by *human papillomavirus (HPV)*, especially *types 6 and 11*. After excision it tends to recur, but it rarely transforms to malignancy. Morphology - pedunculated red papillary
excrescences <br><br>{{c1::Condyloma acuminatum}}

This cancer prevalence is related to carcinogens within
*smegma accumulating under the foreskin*, as well as *HPV types 16 and 18*. Most cases occur in men between ages 40 and 70 years & presents as *epithelial thickening
on the glans* <br><br>{{c1::Penile squamous cell carcinoma}}

Histologically, which STD 
can be *nodular gummas or diffuse interstitial inflammation with edema*, lymphoplasmacytic inflammation, and obliterative
endarteritis. <br><br>{{c1::Syphilis}}

Tumor that commonly involve the *proximal spermatic cord*; in some cases, however, fat around the cord only represents retroperitoneal
adipose tissue that has been pulled into the inguinal
canal with a hernia sac is ___ <br><br>{{c1::Lipomas}}

An uncommon neoplasm (1% to 2% of all germ cell tumors) of the testicles, typically occurring in *older patients > 65 yrs*. indolent tumors with
*little tendency to metastasize*; they are not associated with
ITGCN with *mucoid cysts*. <br><br>{{c1::SPERMATOCYTIC SEMINOMA}}

This is typically caused by
organisms associated with UTI (e.g., E. coli, other Gram-negative rods, enterococci, and staphylococci) on the *PROSTATE*. Fever, chills, dysuria, and a boggy, markedly
*tender prostate*. <br><br>{{c1::Acute bacterial prostatitis}}

The *most common
form of prostatitis* similar to chronic bacterial prostatitis but
*without recurrent urinary tract infections*. <br><br>{{c1::Chronic abacterial prostatitis}}

A Gram-negative bacillus and the major cause of *bacterial vaginitis*; patients present
with a thin, green-gray, *fishy-smelling discharge*. Such
infections can precipitate premature labor <br><br>{{c1::Gardnerella vaginalis (BV)}}

Which carcinoma typically arise in the *setting
of long-standing lichen sclerosus or squamous cell hyperplasia*; the
immediately pre-malignant lesions are called *differentiated VIN*. Presents as *infiltrating nests and tongues* with prominent *keratin pearls* <br><br>{{c1::Keratinizing squamous cell carcinomas}}

An uncommon, highly malignant vaginal tumor in infants and children consisting of *embryonal rhabdomyoblasts*. The
tumors are *polypoid, bulky* masses composed of *grape-like clusters
(sarcoma botryoides)* that can protrude from the vagina. Oval nuclei with cytoplasmic protrusions. <br><br>{{c1::Embryonal rhabdomyosarcoma}}

Which infection can present with abnormal bleeding, pain,
discharge, and/or infertility; histologically, there is endometrial
plasma cell and macrophage infiltration. It occurs in patients with *PID & IUD* <br><br>{{c1::Chronic endometritis}}

Most common placental Infections that can cause *infection of the chorionic membranes
(acute chorioamnionitis)* that then produces *premature membrane
rupture* and preterm delivery <br><br>{{c1::Ascending (usually bacterial) infections}}

A severe form associated with *seizures and coma*. Patients can also present with hypercoagulability,
renal failure, and pulmonary edema; 10% develop HELLP
syndrome (Hemolysis, Elevated liver enzymes, Low platelet count) <br><br>{{c1::Eclampsia}}

